Tony Blair said he would take the opportunity to return as British prime minister - but admits that a comeback is unlikely.
In an interview tonight on the occasion of the fifth anniversary of his resignation from the office of the 59-year-old announced his views on various domestic issues.
Since his retirement in June 2007 after a decade as head of state, Blair has largely avoided to comment on British politics, and his comments mostly limited to the foreign policy and its role as an envoy of the Quartet of peacemakers in the Middle East.
When asked if he would like to return in the premiership, Blair was quoted by the Evening Standard of London with the words: "Yes, sure, but it is unlikely that this happens, so ..."
